Virtual Visit Follow-up -- HIV Clinic
Visit was conducted via Virtual Visit Telehealth Service: Telehealth Video/Audio Equipment. Reason visit converted to virtual/phone visit: patient preference/request. The patient agreed to speak over video for this virtual encounter. Two patient identifiers confirmed.
A total of 15 minutes was spent providing care via virtual encounter with the patient.
Subjective:
HPI: Falicia Thomas Jahnke is a 52 year old female with HIV, currently experiencing a virtual visit for management of their HIV infection.
Reports developing ringworm on scalp over the past 2 weeks. Has 2 discrete, circular areas on the posterior scalp that are itchy. Denies redness, bumps, bleeding or pain. Has been applying "blue star ointment" without relief although this causes a burning sensation. No other contacts in the home with a rash
Also requested refill of metformin as she is out. Has enough pills of her other medications to last until her next follow-up at ACCESS.
Current Medications[1]
Past medical, social, including substance and nicotine use, and family history were reviewed with patient.
Domestic violence screen completed: Negative
ROS (positive in bold)
Systemic No fevers, chills, night sweats or weight loss
Eye No blurry vision, eye redness.
Ear/Nose No nasal congestion. No hearing loss
Throat No oral sores, thrush or difficulty swallowing.
No bleeding gums, tooth ache or loosening of teeth
Respiratory Denies wheezing or shortness of breath.
No cough; no hemoptysis.
Cardiovascular No chest pain, palpitations. No syncopal episodes, no edema
Gastrointestinal/ Liver No dysphagia, abdominal pain, no regurgitation.
No diarrhea; no constipation or blood in stool.
Heme/Lymph No adenopathy or easy bruising
GU No dysuria, hematuria, or genital lesions.
No urinary hesitancy or incontinence.
Musculoskeletal No joint pain, stiffness, or swelling. No lower back pain.
Skin rashes or lesions. No hair loss.
Neuro/Psych No headaches. No weakness or numbness.
Objective:
No vitals obtained nor physical exam performed during virtual encounter.
Patient spoke without disturbances in speech. No signs of cough, dyspnea, pain or confusion during encounter.
The total time spent in direct discussion with the patient was 8 minutes
Assessment & Plan:
Tinea corporis
- on scalp
- start terbinafine BID until resolved
DM 2
- well controlled, A1c 5.9 5/8/25
- refilled metformin ER
HIV Disease
- well control of HIV infection. CD4 1440/39%, VL 29 5/8/25
- continue Triumeq (DTG/ABC/3TC)
- PJP prophylaxis is not necessary
- team visit scheduled on 6/9/26
Andrea Kwan, PA-C
ACCESS Clinic
